Project - Plant Seedling Image Classifier¶

Background:¶

Can you differentiate a weed from a crop seedling? The ability to do so effectively can mean better crop yields and better stewardship of the environment. The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 species at several growth stages.

Objective:¶

The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo.

Dataset:¶

The original files are from Kaggle:

https://www.kaggle.com/c/plant-seedlings-classification/data?select=train

Due to the large volume of data, the images were converted to images.npy file and the labels are also put into the Labels.csv.

  • images.npy
  • Label.csv

Data Preprocessing¶

In [8]:
# Create X dataset from copying 'images' dataset
X = images.copy()
In [9]:
# Normalize the image data
X = X.astype('float32') # Convert to float type
X /= 255.0              # Divide by 255 to normalize
In [10]:
# Apply Gaussian Blur

Build CNN Model¶

In [15]:
# Clear the session and set a random seed
tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
tf.random.set_seed(1)

# Initiate the model and define layers
nn_1 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=X_train.shape[1:], activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),
                                   MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)),
                                   Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),
                                   MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)),
                                   Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'valid'),
                                   MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)),
                                   Flatten(),
                                   Dense(units = 512, activation = 'relu'),
                                   Dropout(0.5),
                                   Dense(units = 128, activation = 'relu'),
                                   Dense(units = 12, activation = 'softmax')]) 

# Print a summary
print(nn_1.summary())

Train the Model¶

In [17]:
%%time
# Add constraints and record best weights to resume 
callbacks = [
    EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',             # Monitor validation loss history
        min_delta=0.001,                # Stop training when validation loss is no longer improving by at least 0.001
        patience=10,                    # Look at validation loss improvement over the last 10 epochs
        verbose=1), 
]

# Train the model
nn_1.fit(X_train, y_train, validation_data = (X_test, y_test), callbacks=callbacks, epochs = 40, verbose = 1)

Visualize Predictions on Several Images¶

In [24]:
# Create function predict for an individual image
def predict_image(img):
    prediction = nn_1_trained.predict(np.expand_dims(img, axis = 0))
    print('\nImage Class Probablities:', prediction)
    print('\n         Predicted class: %.0f' % np.argmax(prediction))
    plt.figure()
    plt.imshow(img);

Summary¶

  • The goal of this project was to create a CNN classifier capable of predicting a plant's species from a photo.
  • We tried only one CNN model architecture and were able to achieve about 78% prediction accuracy with it.
  • We could probably improve this greatly by testing additional CNN architectures.
  • We could test additional CNN models using train and test data, then test our final model on the validation data.
